                        <h4>Ho Chi Minh City (Saigon)</h4>
                        <p>Sai Gon, also commonly known as Ho Chi Minh City, was once the capital of the French colony and currently a metropolitan area covering most parts of Vietnam’s south-east region. The city is well-known for its diversified cuisines and bustling nightlife.</p>
                        <p>Suggested places to see: The Notre-Dame Cathedral Basilica and The Central Post Office, of which designs are in European architectural style, are some must-visit destinations when you stay in Sai Gon. Moreover, you can learn about the history of war by visiting The Reunification Palace, The War Museum or Cu Chi Tunnels. Don’t forget to take a boat trip around Mekong Delta for some adventures.</p>
                        <p>Peak season: Lunar New Year Festival (Tet Festival) often falls between late January and mid February, which is among the most important holidays in Vietnam. Officially, the festival includes the 1st, 2nd and 3rd day in Lunar Calendar; however, Vietnamese people often spend about nearly a month to celebrate this special event. </p>
                        <p>Low season: Both domestic and international tourism volumes fall during the period from mid February to mid March.</p>
                        <p>Suggested places to see: The Notre-Dame Cathedral Basilica and The Central Post Office, of which designs are in European architectural style, are some must-visit destinations when you stay in Sai Gon. Moreover, you can learn about the history of war by visiting The Reunification Palace, The War Museum or Cu Chi Tunnels. Don’t forget to take a boat trip around Mekong Delta for some adventures.</p>
                    </div>
